<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
Seems as though I keep seeing a lot of the same ideas listed over and over again. (i.e. Push/pull, invisibilty). While they would be nice, i doubt that Mythic would ever take the time to implement them because of the probable huge dev time involved, as well as the griefing potential of the spells. Just being realistic. Same with stuns, just dont see Mythic adding this to the Sorc. The trend is to reduce the use of stuns/mez in RvR, so doubting they will be adding it to anyone, though it would be nice.<P>What I'd like to see added and is doable, I think:<P>Spells that give us the ability to allow our pets to actually protect us, such as /guard,/protect/ intercept, and so on, just as some PC tanks can do. The reality of current RvR is such that its is not realistic for a tank class to stand by you (the caster) soley to /protect you. When Mythic desgined the game, This was likely one of the possible defensive stratgies the developers took into account when viewing mage types. In reality, it isn't working because of the nature of RvR and relative closeness required for this tactic to be used. By allowing pets to substitue for a tank class, (after all the purpose of having a pet is to protect your paper-wearing self), you again put this tactic back into that game. The level of protection can be increased incrementally with spec matter level, thereby forcing a choice between the Body line for more offensive spells and another CC option, or a more defensive posture, with some dmg (Dot). IMO, this fits the Sorc class well, does not overpower the class, gives us a pet that is more useful and has versatility. <P>Drain mana or end, I would think, would not be too hard to implement, but this alone wouldn't be worth speccing matter (at least not to me), though interesting. Might be workable to add these along with the pet "buffs" mentioned above, and a better Dot, and maybe some kind of weak AE DD.<P>DoTs should either be made stackable, or much harder hitting. At present, the DoT cannot even kill a green.
</FONT>
